\begin{abstract}
A formulation is presented that establishes consistency between stress-field solutions based on the method of characteristics and generalized limit equilibrium (GLE) procedures for the evaluation of pseudo-static active earth pressure on a smooth vertical wall. Seismic loading is incorporated through rotation of the gravity field following Cheng~\cite{Cheng2003}, which induces a transition zone adjacent to the wall. For cohesionless soils, the resulting stress field exhibits self-similarity, leading to a linear pressure distribution and a resultant acting at approximately one-third of the wall height. Extension to cohesive–frictional materials indicates that, while cohesion modifies the magnitude of the thrust, the overall distribution remains close to linear under seismic loading. By enforcing equivalence of global force and moment, a constant interslice force inclination parameter $\lambda$ may be identified within a GLE framework. The vertical stress amplification at the wall predicted by the stress-field solution is independently corroborated by the dynamic rocking mechanism of Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024}. Slide2 verification confirms $FS=1.000$ at the predicted $\lambda$ for $c’=0$, 100, and 200~psf, with $\lambda$ varying by less than $1^\circ$ over this range.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Evaluation of seismic earth pressures on retaining structures is commonly performed using limit equilibrium approaches derived from pseudo-static assumptions. Among these, formulations based on Coulomb-type wedges and their extensions~\cite{morgensternPrice1965} remain widely used in practice. In parallel, stress-field solutions derived from plasticity theory~\cite{sokolovskii1965} offer a rigorous description of the stress state but are less frequently applied in routine design.

Despite their common objective, these approaches are typically developed independently. The relationship between stress-field solutions and generalized limit equilibrium (GLE) formulations—particularly with respect to the selection of interslice force inclination—has not been explicitly established. This technical note presents a complete derivation that links Sokolovskii stress-field solutions to generalized limit equilibrium procedures for pseudo-static active earth pressure on a smooth vertical wall with horizontal backfill. The resulting practical two-step procedure allows direct determination of the equivalent constant interslice force inclination~$\lambda$ while reproducing the resultant location obtained from the stress field. All equations, tables, and verification results are provided herein.

\section{Problem statement}
This study considers a semi-infinite, weightful soil mass behind a smooth vertical wall with horizontal backfill surface and pseudo-static seismic loading. Given $\varphi’$ (friction angle), $c’$ (cohesion), $\gamma$ (unit weight), $\kh$ (horizontal seismic coefficient), $H$ (wall height), and $\delta_{\text{wall}}=0$ (smooth wall), the objective is to determine the wall pressure distribution $p(z)$, the total thrust $P_{AE}$, the resultant location $h$, and the equivalent GLE interslice force inclination $\lambda$.

\section{Governing equations}
\subsection{Equilibrium (2D, pseudo-static body forces)}
At every point $(x,z)$ in the soil mass,
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial \sigma_x}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial \tau_{xz}}{\partial z} &= \kh,\gamma, \label{eq:1a}\
\frac{\partial \tau_{xz}}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial \sigma_z}{\partial z} &= \gamma, \label{eq:1b}
\end{align}
where $z$ is depth below the surface (positive downward) and $x$ is horizontal distance from the wall (positive into the backfill).

\subsection{Mohr–Coulomb yield condition}
At every point in the active zone, the stress state lies on the Mohr–Coulomb failure envelope,
\begin{equation}
R = \tilde{\sigma},\sin\varphi’, \label{eq:2}
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\text{mean}}=\frac{\sigma_1+\sigma_3}{2},\qquad
R=\frac{\sigma_1-\sigma_3}{2},\qquad
\tilde{\sigma}=\sigma_{\text{mean}}+c’\cot\varphi’.
\end{equation}

\subsection{Stress components in Cartesian coordinates}
The stress tensor at any point is expressed in terms of $\tilde{\sigma}$ and the principal stress rotation angle $\psi$ (angle of $\sigma_1$ from vertical, measured counter-clockwise):
\begin{align}
\sigma_x &= \sigma_{\text{mean}} - R\cos(2\psi), \label{eq:3a}\
\sigma_z &= \sigma_{\text{mean}} + R\cos(2\psi), \label{eq:3b}\
\tau_{xz} &= -R\sin(2\psi). \label{eq:3c}
\end{align}
Substituting Eq.~\eqref{eq:2} and $\sigma_{\text{mean}}=\tilde{\sigma}-c’\cot\varphi’$ gives
\begin{align}
\sigma_x &= \tilde{\sigma}\bigl[1-\sin\varphi’\cos(2\psi)\bigr]-c’\cot\varphi’, \label{eq:3ap}\
\sigma_z &= \tilde{\sigma}\bigl[1+\sin\varphi’\cos(2\psi)\bigr]-c’\cot\varphi’, \label{eq:3bp}\
\tau_{xz} &= -\tilde{\sigma}\sin\varphi’\sin(2\psi). \label{eq:3cp}
\end{align}

\section{Rankine zone (far from wall)}
\subsection{Cohesionless backfill ($c’=0$)}
Far from the wall, the stress field is self-similar: all stresses scale linearly with depth $z$. This follows from the absence of a length scale when $c’=0$. Let
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\text{mean}}=s\gamma z,
\end{equation}
where $s$ is dimensionless. In the self-similar field, $\partial(\cdot)/\partial x=0$, and Eq.~\eqref{eq:1b} gives
\begin{equation}
\sigma_z=\gamma z. \label{eq:4}
\end{equation}
Equation~\eqref{eq:1a} gives
\begin{equation}
\tau_{xz}=\kh\gamma z. \label{eq:5}
\end{equation}
Substituting Eqs.~\eqref{eq:4}–\eqref{eq:5} into Eqs.~\eqref{eq:3b}–\eqref{eq:3c} with $R=s\gamma z\sin\varphi’$ yields
\begin{align}
s+s\sin\varphi’\cos(2\psi) &= 1, \label{eq:6}\
-s\sin\varphi’\sin(2\psi) &= \kh. \label{eq:7}
\end{align}
Eliminating $\psi$ by squaring and adding gives
\begin{equation}
(1-s)^2+\kh^2=s^2\sin^2\varphi’\quad\Rightarrow\quad s^2\cos^2\varphi’ -2s+(1+\kh^2)=0. \label{eq:8}
\end{equation}
The active root corresponds to the smaller $s$:
\begin{equation}
s = \frac{2-\sqrt{4-4\cos^2\varphi’(1+\kh^2)}}{2\cos^2\varphi’}. \label{eq:9}
\end{equation}
Define
\begin{align}
K_x &\equiv \frac{\sigma_x}{\sigma_z}=2s-1, \label{eq:10}\
\lambda_{\text{Rankine}} &\equiv \frac{\tau_{xz}}{\sigma_x}=\frac{\kh}{2s-1}=\frac{\kh}{K_x}, \label{eq:11}\
\psi_R &= \tfrac{1}{2},\operatorname{atan2}(-2\kh,,1-K_x). \label{eq:12}
\end{align}

\subsection{Cohesive–frictional backfill ($c’>0$)}
For $c’>0$, the problem is not self-similar because the dimensionless cohesion ratio
\begin{equation}
m=\frac{c’}{\gamma z}
\end{equation}
depends on depth. At each depth, the quadratic for $s$ becomes
\begin{equation}
A s^2 + B s + C = 0, \label{eq:13}
\end{equation}
with
\begin{equation}
A=\cos^2\varphi’,\qquad B=-2\bigl(1+m\sin\varphi’\cos\varphi’\bigr),\qquad C=1+\kh^2-m^2\cos^2\varphi’.
\end{equation}
The active root is
\begin{equation}
s(z)=\frac{-B-\sqrt{B^2-4AC}}{2A}. \label{eq:14}
\end{equation}
When $B^2-4AC<0$, no active state exists at that depth (tension zone). The critical depth $z_{cr}$ where the discriminant vanishes defines the tension crack depth.

Depth-varying quantities are
\begin{equation}
K_x(z)=2s(z)-1, \label{eq:15}
\end{equation}
and $\psi_R(z)$ follows from the stress-tensor inversion using Eqs.~\eqref{eq:3a}–\eqref{eq:3c}:
\begin{align}
\cos(2\psi_R) &= \frac{\sigma_z-\sigma_{x,R}}{2R},\qquad
\sin(2\psi_R) = -\frac{\tau_{xz}}{R}, \label{eq:16}
\end{align}
with $\sigma_{x,R}=(2s(z)-1)\gamma z$, $\sigma_z=\gamma z$, $\tau_{xz}=\kh\gamma z$, and $R=\tilde{\sigma}(z)\sin\varphi’$.

\section{Fan zone}
Seismic loading is introduced through a rotation of the gravity vector by an angle $\varepsilon=\arctan\kh$ following the approach of Cheng~\cite{Cheng2003}. This transformation permits the governing equations to retain their static form while incorporating inertial effects. The modified body force is $\gamma’=\gamma\sqrt{1+\kh^2}$.

For a smooth vertical wall under static loading ($\kh=0$), there is no fan zone: the entire domain is a Rankine zone with parallel straight slip lines, and the Coulomb solution is exact (Sokolovskii~\cite{sokolovskii1965}, Chapter~11 and Chapter~25). Under pseudo-static seismic loading, the smooth vertical wall becomes an inclined surface in the rotated coordinate system. This inclination creates a transition (fan) zone between the Rankine zone and the wall in which stress characteristics rotate to satisfy boundary conditions. This feature arises naturally from the rotated stress state and differs from the classical static solution.

For cohesionless materials, the absence of an intrinsic stress scale leads to a self-similar solution in which stresses vary linearly with depth. The corresponding lateral pressure distribution is therefore linear, and the resultant force acts at approximately one-third of the wall height.

Between the Rankine zone and the wall, the stress field transitions through the fan zone where $\psi$ changes from $\psi_R$ to the wall value. Along a characteristic (slip line) for $c’=0$,
\begin{equation}
\frac{\diff \tilde{\sigma}}{\tilde{\sigma}} = 2\sin\varphi’,\diff\psi. \label{eq:17}
\end{equation}
Integrating from the Rankine boundary to an arbitrary point yields
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\sigma}(\psi)=\tilde{\sigma}*R\exp\bigl[2\sin\varphi’(\psi-\psi_R)\bigr]. \label{eq:18}
\end{equation}
Note that the sign convention adopted here ($\psi$ counter-clockwise from vertical) gives $\psi_R<0$ for $\kh>0$, and $\psi$ increases from $\psi_R$ to $\psi*{\text{wall}}=0$ toward the wall. Eq.~\eqref{eq:18} therefore implies $\tilde{\sigma}$ increases toward the wall (fan-zone amplification). Define the amplification factor
\begin{equation}
A_{\text{fan}}=\exp\bigl(-2\sin\varphi’,\psi_R\bigr), \label{eq:19}
\end{equation}
which is greater than unity because $\psi_R<0$. Then
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\sigma}_{\text{wall}}=\tilde{\sigma}*R,A*{\text{fan}}. \label{eq:20}
\end{equation}

\section{Wall boundary conditions (smooth wall)}
At the smooth wall face ($x=0$),
\begin{equation}
\tau_{xz,\text{wall}}=0. \label{eq:21a}
\end{equation}
From Eq.~\eqref{eq:3c}, $R\sin(2\psi_{\text{wall}})=0$ and $R>0$ in the active zone, hence
\begin{equation}
\psi_{\text{wall}}=0. \label{eq:21b}
\end{equation}
At the wall, $\sigma_1$ is vertical and $\sigma_3$ is horizontal.

\section{Wall stresses and pressure}
\subsection{Cohesionless backfill ($c’=0$)}
At the wall with $\psi_{\text{wall}}=0$,
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\sigma}*{\text{wall}}=s\gamma z,A*{\text{fan}}. \label{eq:22}
\end{equation}
The wall stresses are
\begin{align}
\sigma_{x,\text{wall}} &= \tilde{\sigma}*{\text{wall}}(1-\sin\varphi’), \label{eq:23}\
\sigma*{z,\text{wall}} &= \tilde{\sigma}*{\text{wall}}(1+\sin\varphi’). \label{eq:24}
\end{align}
Define the wall pressure coefficient
\begin{equation}
K*{\text{wall}}=s,A_{\text{fan}},(1-\sin\varphi’). \label{eq:25}
\end{equation}
The vertical stress ratio at the wall is
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma_{z,\text{wall}}}{\gamma z}=s,A_{\text{fan}},(1+\sin\varphi’). \label{eq:26}
\end{equation}
The wall pressure distribution is linear:
\begin{equation}
p(z)=K_{\text{wall}}\gamma z. \label{eq:27}
\end{equation}
Therefore, the pressure distribution is triangular and the resultant location is exact:
\begin{equation}
h=\frac{H}{3}. \label{eq:hH3}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Key observation: vertical stress amplification at the wall}
From Eq.~\eqref{eq:26}, the vertical stress at the wall is not geostatic. The fan zone amplification creates additional vertical stress:
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma_{z,\text{wall}}}{\sigma_{z,\text{geostatic}}}=s,A_{\text{fan}},(1+\sin\varphi’). \label{eq:28}
\end{equation}
Example ($\varphi’=34^\circ$, $\kh=0.16$): $s=0.6646$, $\psi_R=-12.75^\circ$, $A_{\text{fan}}=1.283$, and $\sigma_{z,\text{wall}}/(\gamma z)=1.329$.

\subsection{Numerical verification: $K_{\text{wall}}\approx K_{AE}$ (Mononobe–Okabe) for $c’=0$}
For $c’=0$, smooth wall, and level backfill, the derived coefficient
\begin{equation}
K_{\text{wall}}=s,\exp(2\sin\varphi’,\psi_R),(1-\sin\varphi’)
\end{equation}
matches the Mononobe–Okabe coefficient $K_{AE}$ for $\delta=0$ (verified numerically; example above gives $K_{\text{wall}}\approx 0.376$ and $K_{AE}\approx 0.378$).

\subsection{Cohesive–frictional backfill ($c’>0$)}
For $c’>0$, the pressure at each depth $z$ requires a depthwise computation:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*),leftmargin=*]
\item Solve Eq.~\eqref{eq:14} for $s(z)$ with $m=c’/(\gamma z)$.
\item Compute $\psi_R(z)$ from Eq.~\eqref{eq:16}.
\item Apply fan zone amplification:
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\sigma}*{\text{wall}}(z)=\tilde{\sigma}*R(z)\exp\bigl(2\sin\varphi’,\psi_R(z)\bigr).
\end{equation}
\item Compute wall pressure:
\begin{equation}
p(z)=\sigma*{x,\text{wall}}(z)=\tilde{\sigma}*{\text{wall}}(z)(1-\sin\varphi’)-c’\cot\varphi’.
\end{equation}
\item If $p(z)<0$, set $p(z)=0$ (tension zone).
\end{enumerate}
The pressure is no longer linear in $z$: near the surface $p(z)=0$ for $z<z_{cr}$, and at depth the solution approaches the $c’=0$ form. On the Sokolovskii curved slip lines the pressure distribution is nonlinear and the resultant acts at $h<H/3$ with increasing cohesion. However, on the planar failure surface routinely employed in GLE analyses, seismic interslice shear forces restore an approximately linear distribution, yielding $h\approx H/3$ for the verified range of parameters ($c’/\gamma H=0$ to $0.056$, $\kh=0.16$, $\varphi’=34^\circ$). Under static loading ($\kh=0$, $\lambda=0$), $h$ drops with increasing $c’$ (e.g.\ $h/H=0.199$ at $c’=200$~psf).

\section{From Sokolovskii to constant-$\lambda$ GLE closure}
\subsection{Physical mechanism: vertical stress redistribution}
The fan zone amplifies vertical stress at the wall (Eq.~\eqref{eq:28}). In the GLE framework, the same redistribution occurs through interslice shear forces $X_i$. Consider slice $i$ in a Morgenstern–Price (M–P) formulation. The vertical force balance gives
\begin{equation}
N\cos\alpha + F\sin\alpha = W + E_{i+1}\sin(\delta_{i+1}) - E_i\sin(\delta_i), \label{eq:29}
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ is the base inclination, $W$ is slice weight, $(N,F)$ are base normal and shear, and $E_i$ acts on the left face at inclination $\delta_i$. For the wall-adjacent slice (slice 1) with smooth wall, $\delta_1=0$ and $X_1=0$, so
\begin{equation}
V_{\text{base}} = W + X_2, \label{eq:30}
\end{equation}
with $X_2=E_2\sin\delta_2>0$ pushing downward on slice 1. The interslice shear from the interior adds vertical load to the wall-adjacent slice, increasing $\sigma_z$ beyond $\gamma z$, which is the direct analogue of the fan-zone amplification.

\subsection{Deterministic two-step procedure for $\lambda$}
The constant-$\lambda$ value cannot be recovered from a simple average of stress ratios because the GLE moment equation contains nonlinear coupling through the backward march. This study therefore uses two independent steps.

\paragraph{Step 1: Sokolovskii $\rightarrow h$.}
Compute $p(z)$ as described above and integrate to obtain
\begin{align}
P_{AE} &= \int_0^H p(z),\diff z, \label{eq:31}\
h &= \frac{\int_0^H p(z)(H-z),\diff z}{P_{AE}}. \label{eq:32}
\end{align}
For $c’=0$, $h=H/3$ exactly. For $c’>0$ on the Sokolovskii curved slip line, $h<H/3$. On the planar failure surface under seismic loading, $h\approx H/3$ for all $c’$.

\paragraph{Step 2: GLE moment equation $\rightarrow \lambda$.}
Run the M–P backward march at the critical failure angle $\alpha$ with constant interslice inclination $\delta$ (smooth wall: $\delta_1=0$). All equations are evaluated at $FS=1.0$. The backward-march equations are
\begin{align}
A_i &= W_i(\cos\delta_i - \kh\sin\delta_i) - c’ L_i\sin(\alpha-\delta_i), \
D_i &= \cos(\alpha-\delta_i) + \tan\varphi’\sin(\alpha-\delta_i), \
N_i &= \frac{A_i - E_{i+1}\sin(\delta_i-\delta_{i+1})}{D_i}, \
F_i &= N_i\tan\varphi’ + c’ L_i, \
E_i &= \frac{E_{i+1}\cos\delta_{i+1} + \kh W_i + N_i\sin\alpha - F_i\cos\alpha}{\cos\delta_i}.
\end{align}
The moment arm $h$ depends on $\delta$ through the $N_i$ distribution. A binary search on $\delta$ is performed until the GLE-computed $h$ matches the Sokolovskii value from Step~1. The resulting $\delta$ is reported as the constant-$\lambda$ GLE value.

\subsection{Critical failure angle}
The critical angle $\alpha$ is determined from the GLE backward march at $\lambda=0$ by sweeping $\alpha$ to maximize $P_{AE}$. For $\varphi’=34^\circ$, $c’=0$, $\alpha_{\text{crit}}\approx 54.8^\circ$; for $\varphi’=34^\circ$, $c’=200\ \text{psf}$, $\alpha_{\text{crit}}\approx 55.8^\circ$.

