\section{Comparison and interpretation}
\subsection{Stress field on the planar failure surface}
For $\varphi’=34^\circ$ and $\kh=0.16$, the planar failure surface at $\alpha\approx 54.3^\circ$ lies entirely within the fan zone. The Rankine-zone boundary angle from the toe is $\theta_{\max}=40.75^\circ$, while the planar surface subtends $\theta=35.7^\circ$. As a result, the Sokolovskii stress field on the planar surface is not at full yield; the mobilization ratio is $\tau_s/\sigma_n\approx 0.538$ versus $\tan\varphi’\approx 0.675$ (about 80% mobilized). In contrast, the GLE enforces $FS=1.0$ on the prescribed planar surface. The difference is accommodated by the GLE through redistribution of $N$ via $\lambda$, which adjusts $h$ while maintaining overall equilibrium.

\subsection{Why $\lambda_{\text{GLE}}\neq \kh/K_x$}
The Rankine-zone ratio $\kh/K_x$ is the shear-to-normal ratio on internal vertical planes in the Rankine zone, whereas $\lambda$ is the interslice force inclination that reproduces the wall resultant height for a prescribed planar surface with a smooth wall condition ($\lambda\to 0$ at the wall). The two values differ because (a) the wedge includes both fan and Rankine regions, (b) the wall boundary condition forces zero wall shear, and (c) the M–P force resolution introduces nonlinear coupling.

