\section{Extension to cohesive–frictional backfill: practical procedure}
For cohesive–frictional materials under seismic loading, the pressure distribution on a planar failure surface remains close to linear. The following self-contained procedure is recommended:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\textbf{Step \arabic*:},leftmargin=*]
\item Compute $P_{AE}$ from the GLE backward march at $\lambda=0$ on the critical planar surface. In the verified cases this value is only weakly sensitive to $\lambda$, and it accounts for cohesion and tension-crack effects.
\item Adopt $h\approx H/3$ for the point of application.
\item Select the constant $\lambda$ from the $c’=0$ table (Table~\ref{tab:c0}) corresponding to the design $\kh$ and $\varphi’$. Over the verified range $c’/\gamma H=0$ to $0.056$, $\lambda$ varies by less than $1^\circ$.
\end{enumerate}

For static loading ($\kh=0$), $\lambda=0$ and $h<H/3$ with increasing $c’$ because no interslice shear is present to redistribute vertical stress.

\textbf{Remark on the Sokolovskii curved slip line.} The Sokolovskii stress field on the curved slip line gives $h/H=0.280$ for $c’=200$~psf ($\varphi’=34^\circ$, $\kh=0.16$), which is below $H/3$. This applies to the curved failure surface, not the planar surface used in the GLE. The superposition structure of Sokolovskii~\cite{sokolovskii1965} (Chapter~25, Part~5) supports this distinction: the weight term $q_2=\gamma r,q_0$ is always linear with depth (self-similar wedge), and only the cohesion/surcharge term introduces a uniform (depth-independent) offset.

