\section{Spatially varying $\lambda$}
The Sokolovskii stress field produces a spatially varying shear ratio: at the wall face $\tau_{xz}/\sigma_x=0$ (smooth wall), the ratio increases through the fan zone, and approaches the Rankine-zone constant $\kh/K_x$ in the interior. The constant-$\lambda$ assumption replaces this spatial variation with a single scalar that produces the same moment arm $h$. A half-sine distribution used in some software approximates this pattern; its area-average ($2/\pi$ times its peak) can be close to the equivalent constant value.

\section{Connection to dynamic vertical stress amplification}

\subsection{Sokolovskii and Madabhushi: independent corroboration}
The vertical stress amplification at the wall derived in Eq.~\eqref{eq:28} has an independent corroboration in recent experimental and numerical work. Madabhushi and Haigh~\cite{Madabhushi2022} and Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024} demonstrated through dynamic centrifuge tests and finite-element analyses that purely horizontal shaking induces dynamic normal vertical effective stresses via ``rocking’’ of the retained soil body. Their measurements showed increases of up to 100% of geostatic values for dual-row sheet pile walls.

Both frameworks arrive at the same conclusion—$\sigma_z$ at the wall exceeds $\gamma z$ under horizontal loading—but from independent theoretical bases:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item \textbf{Sokolovskii (plasticity):} The fan-zone stress rotation amplifies $\sigma_z$ by the factor $s,A_{\text{fan}}(1+\sin\varphi’)$, a static equilibrium result from the method of characteristics extended to pseudo-static loading following Cheng~\cite{Cheng2003}.
\item \textbf{Madabhushi (dynamics):} Horizontal acceleration induces out-of-phase vertical accelerations through rotational inertia (rocking), producing dynamic $\sigma_z$ oscillations.
\end{itemize}

Both frameworks also agree on the relationship between horizontal and vertical stress at a smooth wall. In the Sokolovskii solution at $\psi_{\text{wall}}=0$,
\begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma_{x,\text{wall}}}{\sigma_{z,\text{wall}}} = \frac{1-\sin\varphi’}{1+\sin\varphi’} = K_A\text{ (static Rankine)}.
\end{equation}
Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024} reach the same conclusion: the limiting horizontal stress is the static Rankine coefficient applied to the (non-geostatic) dynamic vertical stress, i.e.\ $\sigma’*h = K_A \times \sigma’*{v,\text{dynamic}}$. Dynamic earth pressure coefficients that embed both acceleration and partial mobilization are therefore unnecessary.

\subsection{Resultant location under CAM-DYN rocking}
Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024} proposed the CAM-DYN analytical method in which the dynamic vertical effective stress at depth $z$ is
\begin{equation}
\sigma’_v(z) = \gamma z\bigl[1 \pm \eta(z)\bigr], \qquad \eta(z) = 3,\frac{z}{b},\frac{a(t)}{g},
\label{eq:camdyn}
\end{equation}
where $b$ is the width of the retained soil body and $a(t)$ is the instantaneous horizontal acceleration. The factor~3 arises from vertical and moment equilibrium of a horizontal slice assuming linear stress redistribution across $b$.

The horizontal pressure on a smooth wall is then quadratic in depth:
\begin{equation}
p_h(z) = K\gamma z + K\gamma,\frac{3,a(t)}{g,b},z^2 \equiv Az + Bz^2.
\end{equation}

Integrating for the total force and the moment about the base:
\begin{align}
F &= \int_0^H (Az + Bz^2),\diff z = \frac{AH^2}{2} + \frac{BH^3}{3}, \
M_{\text{base}} &= \int_0^H (Az + Bz^2)(H-z),\diff z = \frac{AH^3}{6} + \frac{BH^4}{12}.
\end{align}

The resultant location from the base is
\begin{equation}
\bar{y} = \frac{M_{\text{base}}}{F} = H,\frac{\tfrac{1}{6}+\tfrac{r}{12}}{\tfrac{1}{2}+\tfrac{r}{3}},
\qquad r = \pm,3,\frac{H}{b},\frac{a(t)}{g}.
\label{eq:ybar}
\end{equation}

When $r=0$ (no rocking), $\bar{y}=H/3$, recovering the classical result. For the over-stressed side ($r>0$), the resultant moves below $H/3$; for the under-stressed side ($r<0$), it moves above.

\subsection{Magnitude of the shift from $H/3$}
For the prototype geometry of the centrifuge test (Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024}; $H=20$~m, $b=55$~m, $a/g=0.3$), the shift is
\begin{equation}
r = 3\times\frac{20}{55}\times 0.3 = 0.327,\qquad \bar{y}/H = 0.318 \quad(\text{over-stressed side}).
\end{equation}

This is a 4.5% reduction from $H/3$. Table~\ref{tab:rocking} shows the sensitivity to the ratio $H/b$ and $\kh$. For a single retaining wall where $b$ is effectively large ($b\gg H$), the shift is negligible ($<1$–$3%$ for typical $\kh\le 0.24$). The rocking effect on $h$ is significant only for narrow confined soil bodies (dual-row walls with small $b/H$).

