\section{Illustrative example}
Consider a smooth vertical wall of height $H=30$~ft (9.14~m) retaining a horizontal backfill with $\gamma=120$~pcf (18.9~kN/m$^3$), $\varphi’=34^\circ$, $c’=200$~psf (9.6~kPa), and $\kh=0.16$.
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item The GLE backward march at $\lambda=0$ on the critical surface ($\alpha=55.8^\circ$) yields $P_{AE}=14{,}583$~lb/ft (212.8~kN/m).
\item The resultant is taken at $h\approx H/3=10.0$~ft (3.05~m).
\item From Table~\ref{tab:c0}, $\lambda=17.72^\circ$. Slide2 analysis with a triangular pressure distribution ($0$ to $2P_{AE}/H=972$~psf at the base) returns $FS=1.000$ at $\lambda=16.70^\circ$. The $1^\circ$ difference reflects the modest effect of cohesion on $\lambda$.
\end{itemize}

For comparison, the same soil under static loading ($\kh=0$) gives $P_{AE}=9{,}553$~lb/ft, $h=5.97$~ft ($0.199H$), and $\lambda=0^\circ$.

\section{Key contributions and limitations}
\subsection{Key contributions}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item A consistent relationship between stress-field solutions and generalized limit equilibrium procedures has been established for the evaluation of seismic active earth pressure on smooth vertical walls.
\item For cohesionless soils, the stress field leads to a linear pressure distribution with a resultant acting at approximately one-third of the wall height. Extension to cohesive soils ($c’=0$ to $200$~psf) indicates that this distribution is only moderately affected under seismic loading.
\item By matching global force and moment, a constant interslice force inclination parameter $\lambda$ can be determined, providing a practical bridge between continuum and limit equilibrium methods. The $c’=0$ lambda table provides a close approximation for cohesive soils, with $\lambda$ varying by less than $1^\circ$ over the verified range.
\item The vertical stress amplification at the wall ($\sigma_z>\gamma z$) predicted by the fan-zone mechanism is independently corroborated by the dynamic rocking mechanism of Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024}. Both frameworks yield $\sigma_h/\sigma_v=K_A$ (static Rankine) at the smooth wall.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Limitations}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item The Sokolovskii solution assumes full yield throughout the active zone; for cohesive backfill this may require larger wall movements than occur in service.
\item The planar failure surface used in the GLE is not identical to the curved slip lines of the stress field; for $c’=0$ this does not affect $h$, while for $c’>0$ under static loading ($\kh=0$) a difference exists ($h<H/3$).
\item The constant-$\lambda$ assumption is an approximation; the physical interslice shear varies spatially.
\item The CAM-DYN rocking derivation applies to smooth walls; for rough walls, principal stress rotation at the soil–wall interface must be incorporated (Madabhushi and Westcott~\cite{Madabhushi2024}).
\end{enumerate}

